(1, 'home', 'home page for Strange Fruit', '<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<p>\r\n<h4>\r\n\r\n\r\n</h4>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Strange Fruit is the Master''s project of Caitlin Pollock as a condition of her graduation from Loyola Chicago University.</p>\r\n\r\n<p> This project uses <i>A Red Record</i> written by Ida B. Wells, an investigative reporter from Chicago who launched an anti-lynching campaign in late nineteenth century America.</p>\r\n\r\n<p> The goal of this project is to highlight the activism of Ida B. Wells and attempt to remediate a nineteenth-century pamphlet into a twenty-first century digital tool.</p> \r\n', '', '', '2014-01-27 19:16:40'),
(2, 'documentation', 'information about the 402 framework', '<h2>Strange Fruit: Exploring Ida B. Wells’s <i>A Red Record</i> Project Documentation</h2>\r\n<div id="accordion">\r\n<h3>Introduction</h3>\r\n<div>\r\n<p>Ida B. Wells was an investigative reporter during the late nineteenth century and early twentieth century.  Wells, along with Nellie Bly, is considered one of the first female investigative reporters and a pioneer in the investigative reporting tradition that began with the other muckrakers of the late nineteenth century American journalism. After a family friend, Thomas Moss was lynched, Wells wrote an editorial piece, “Eight Men Lynched” in <i>Free Speech and Headlight</i>, a Memphis newspaper that she co-owned. Her editorial incited death threats and she left Memphis for Chicago, the city with which she would become most closely associated. The lynching of Thomas Moss is most of cited as the spark to Wells’s anti-lynching campaign and the subject of most her writings. From 1892 to 1900, Wells published numerous newspaper articles and three anti-lynching pamphlets: <i>Southern Horrors: Lynch Law in All Its Phases</i> (1892), <i>A Red Record</i>(1895), and <i>Mob Rule in New Orleans</i> (1900). For the completion of the my Master’s Thesis Project and a requirement of graduation from Loyola University Chicago’s Master of Arts in Digital Humanities program, I have chosen to create a digital project from Wells <i>A Red Record</i>.\r\n</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Project Description</h3>\r\n<div>\r\n<p>\r\nThe inspiration for this project is three-fold: to highlight the contributions of Ida B. Wells, one of the first female and African American investigative reporters, to create a research tool to study the culture, laws, and victims of lynching in the United States, and an attempt of remediation; in this case remediating a late 19th century text into a digital tool which a twenty-first century researcher would be recognize and feel comfortable using. As researcher with a library and information science Master’s degree–a scholar-librarian– my goal of the project was to develop a remediated tool that allowed greater access to information and attempt to bridge the gap of the dissemination of information from the nineteenth century to the twenty-first century.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\nOften in the world of black political thought and African American Studies, the timeline of important figures goes from Frederick Douglass to Booker T. Washington and W.E.B. DuBois, to Reverend Martin Luther King, Jr., and Malcolm X. The female leaders of the African American struggle for human rights are conspicuously missing from this discourse, and if they are mentioned,  its only for a fleeting moment. One of the best examples of the influence of the race women is comparing Ida B. Wells’ musings on self-defense with those of Malcolm X, some 70 years later. Ida B. Wells in her publication Southern Horrors wrote:\r\n</p><p>\r\n	“The lesson this teaches and which every Afro-American should ponder well, is that a Winchester rifle should have a place of honor in every black home, and it should be used for that protection which the law refuses to give.”  \r\nThis rationale is later echoed in Malcolm X’s famous 1964  speech, “The Ballot or The Bullet”:\r\n</p><p>\r\n“The only thing that I''ve ever said is that in areas where the government has proven itself either unwilling or unable to  defend the lives  and the property of Negroes, it''s time for Negroes to defend themselves. “\r\n</p><p>\r\nThe connection between Ida B. Wells and Malcolm X is not often remarked upon. In undergraduate courses, Malcolm X is attributed with the development of this school of thought on self-defense  with no acknowledgement for Wells. A project such as this would spark a new interest in Ida B. Wells’s work and piggy back on her recent induction into the Chicago Public Library’s Chicago Literary Hall of Fame.\r\n</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Project Design</h3>\r\n<div>\r\n<p>\r\nThis project features an easy-to-navigate, clean website design with an simple search design and an interactive geographic information systems component. The audience of this project is college undergraduates and professors interested in incorporating this project into their class. My attempt in remediating the <i>A Red Record</i> is to advocate the use of digital pedagogy into research instruction classes and the use of digital projects to facilitate historical research and understanding. The framework was built in Digital Humanities 402 using Javascript, CSS, JQuery, PHP, and a MYSQL database to build a historical digital tool. \r\n</p><p>\r\nDigital projects in African American Studies can help to lend authority to the discipline which is a relatively recent discipline compared to Classics, Comparative Literature, Art History, among others. To encourage pluralism and diversity in research topics, and consequently change the discourse and timeline of important figures, technology is one of the best conduits to accomplish this goal. Through technology information can be more widely disseminated. Digital Humanities projects ease the temporal, geographic, and monetary burdens of humanities scholars to complete research. However, more than just make research easier for scholars, Digital Humanities projects also enhance research through analysis. Digital humanities allow for an almost instantaneous or fluid analysis of the data displayed. The Red Record Online will use GIS to achieve such analysis. The user may look at a map to view just a singular lynching event, or see all the lynchings that occurred in a state, town, year, month, or day. The other component of the project, digitized pages of The Red Record, will allow users to see a particular instance of lynching in context with the other lynchings that Ida B. Wells’s investigated.\r\n</p><p>\r\nStrange Fruit required cooperation among several different institutions, including Loyola University’s Center for Textual Studies and Digital Humanities and University of Chicago’s Special Collections Center. This combined effort will improve and strengthen the Digital Humanities field but also the African American Studies and the Library and Information Science disciplines. Working together builds a closer community and powerful network to achieve greater advancements in the application of technology in humanities research.\r\n</p><p>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Project Conclusions</h3>\r\n<div>\r\n<p>My hope is to have this project continue on  after I have graduated. I hope my future employers will allow me to continue my work on this project. My next goals for this project are individual records for each lynching victim named in <i>A Red Record</i>, recode the text in XML-TEI. \r\n</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>\r\nBibliography\r\n</h3>\r\n<div>\r\n<p>\r\nCarby, Hazel V. Race Men. Cambridge, Mass: Harvard University Press, 1998.\r\n</p><p>\r\nGiddings, Paula. Ida: A Sword Among Lions : Ida B. Wells and the Campaign against Lynching. New York, N.Y.: Amistad, 2008.</p></p>\r\n<p>\r\nMalcolm X. "“Ballot or the Bullet” Speech ( 3 April 1964 )." Oxford African American Studies Center, <a href="http://www.oxfordaasc.com/article/doc/ps-aasc-0008">http://www.oxfordaasc.com/article/doc/ps-aasc-0008</a>. (Accessed Mon Dec 10 01:43:36 EST 2012).</p><p>\r\n</p><p>\r\nWells-Barnett, Ida B and Jacqueline Jones Royster. “The Red Record.” in Southern Horrors and Other Writings: The Anti-Lynching Campaign of Ida B. Wells, 1892-1900. Boston, MA: Bedford Books, 1997.\r\n</p><p>\r\nWells-Barnett, Ida B. and Jacqueline Jones Royster. Southern Horrors and Other Writings: The Anti-Lynching Campaign of Ida B. Wells, 1892-1900. Boston, MA: Bedford Books, 1997.\r\n</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', '2014-01-27 19:16:40'),
